{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_019ng237CtfJECzvUUfyC2du","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Perfect! Now I see it clearly. At line 2061:\n\n```c\nif (found == NULL) {\n    top->value.ov = ucl_hash_insert_object (top->value.ov, elt, false);\n    top->len ++;\n```\n\nWhen a key is not found, `top->len++` is incremented. So `top->len` is the count of UNIQUE KEYS only.\n\nBut at lines 2095 (and in the LL_FOREACH loop at line 515-516 of ucl_emitter.c), when we have multi-value keys with the same key, we use `DL_APPEND (found, elt)` which appends the new value to a linked list of values for that key.\n\nSo yes, my understanding is correct:\n- obj->len = count of unique keys\n- But when emitting to msgpack, the code uses LL_FOREACH to iterate through all values for each key\n- This means the map header reports N unique keys, but actually N+K entries are emitted (where K is the total count of extra values)\n- This causes a mismatch in the msgpack format\n\nThe fix is to make the msgpack emitter only emit the first value for each key (as the comment says it should do).","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1510,"cache_read_input_tokens":74024,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1510},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bd6be942-b918-4cf4-b322-bb66cab50f94","uuid":"f21c06c4-505b-401d-b10b-527e74ed7ec6"}
